271// SECURITY_SRAM_RESV - This 32-bit word indicates the minimum amount of DTCM that the Secure Boot Loader (SBL) reserves for the application, which will not be disturbed by SBL across a reset. The programmed value is rounded up, if necessary, by SBL to the next 256 byte boundary. That value is subtracted from the top of DTCM, resulting in a region at the top of DTCM that becomes the reserved area. Example: Apollo330P has 384KB of DTCM, 0x20000000-0x20005FFF. SRAM_RESV contains 0x3E8, SBL rounds up to 0x400, and reserves the region 0x20005C00 - 0x20005FFF for use by the application. Application data in this region will not be modified by SBL across resets. The region will not be preserved across a POI reset or MRAM recovery operation.
272#define AM_REG_OTP_INFO0_SECURITY_SRAM_RESV_SRAM_RESV_S 0
273#define AM_REG_OTP_INFO0_SECURITY_SRAM_RESV_SRAM_RESV_M 0x000FFFFF
274#define AM_REG_OTP_INFO0_SECURITY_SRAM_RESV_SRAM_RESV(n) (((uint32_t)(n) << 0) & 0x000FFFFF)
275#define AM_REG_OTP_INFO0_SECURITY_SRAM_RESV_SRAM_RESV_Pos 0
276#define AM_REG_OTP_INFO0_SECURITY_SRAM_RESV_SRAM_RESV_Msk 0x000FFFFF
